Pattern 2: Rotated Sorted Arrays
The array was sorted, but someone chopped it and swapped the halves. [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] became [4, 5, 1, 2, 3].

The Concept: No matter where you slice a rotated array, at least one half will always be perfectly sorted. You must identify the sorted half, check if your target falls within its range, and if not, discard it.

Java Blueprint:

Java

public int searchRotated(int[] nums, int target) {
    int left = 0, right = nums.length - 1;
    
    while (left <= right) {
        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
        if (nums[mid] == target) return mid;
        
        // Is the LEFT half perfectly sorted?
        if (nums[left] <= nums[mid]) {
            // Is target inside this sorted left half?
            if (target >= nums[left] && target < nums[mid]) {
                right = mid - 1; // Yes, search here
            } else {
                left = mid + 1;  // No, must be in the right half
            }
        } 
        // Otherwise, the RIGHT half must be perfectly sorted
        else {
            // Is target inside this sorted right half?
            if (target > nums[mid] && target <= nums[right]) {
                left = mid + 1; // Yes, search here
            } else {
                right = mid - 1; // No, must be in the left half
            }
        }
    }
    return -1;
}


